title: Need Help with STL for Prosthesis

description.text:
Hello,
I am in the process of designing prosthesis for a woman that lost 9 fingers. This STL is a scan of her left hand. The STL file I uploaded is way too big to open as a solid body in SolidWorks so I need some help making it smaller. If someone would be able to convert this file into an .xt, .step, or .igs, that would be great. Or even if someone could cut it up into smaller sections so I could create an assembly in SW and use the model that way. Thank you for your help.
If you are able to convert the file or make it smaller; message me to let me know how you would like to send the files. Thank you again for your help. You are defiantly supporting a good cause.

comments.text:
Great concept. However, I ran the command beam(8,1,3,0); it gave me a beam with 8 holes. Rendered and exported as stl. Took it into sketchup, measured the left edge of one hole to the left edge of the 6th one. It reports ~53mm, measured an actual piece of meccano and the same number of holes reports as 64mm. I checked http://www.meccanospares.com/helpandinformation.html and it seems the hole pitch is wrong you would need to change the line
hole_pitch = 12.7;

title: Buddha Seated in Meditation (Dhyanamudra), Chola period, c. 12th century, Art Institute of Chicago

description.text:
India
Tamil Nadu, Nagapattinam Buddha Seated in Meditation (Dhyanamudra), Chola period, c. 12th century Granite
160.0 x 120.2 x 56.3 cm (63 x 47 5/16 x 22 3/16 in.) Restricted gift of Mr. and Mrs. Robert Andrew Brown, 1964.556 Asian Art
Display Unit 401 This meditating Buddha comes from the coastal town of Nagapattinam in southern India, which was, as a result of settlers from Srivijaya (Indonesia), one of the few places where Buddhism was still flourishing in the twelfth century. The Buddhaâwith his elongated earlobes, the wheel marks on his palms, the urna between his brows, and the cranial protuberance covered with snail-shell curlsâis seated in the posture of meditation, with his hands resting on his lap (dhyanamudra), wearing a seemingly diaphanous monastic garment. As in other images from Nagapattinam, a flame emerges out of the Buddhaâs cranial protuberance, probably signifying wisdom. This monumental sculpture carved out of granite originally would have graced a monastic site at Nagapattinam, which is also well known for its Buddhist bronzes. The Tamil inscription covering its back is now no longer legible.
â Entry, Essential Guide, 2013, p. 117. http://www.artic.edu/aic/collections/artwork/21023?search_no=29&index=57

description.text: I made these printable 8mm connector bars to work with the "Platonic Solid Vertices" thing: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:9359. Printing the bars gives the final structure a nice consistent look. The bars are cut at one end to make them stick to the platform, but the round parts make them a good fit for the vertices. I hollowed them out somewhat to be economic about material, but I later realized that the hollow might actually add to the printing time. The thin lines help prevent individal pieces coming loose, I'm having problems with lift so I added the lines as a makeshift precaution. They break off easily once printed. These bars are 12 cm long but can obviously be scaled up (not in ReplicatorG, though, that would scale the radius as well as the length.)

The motion of you hand powers a diode. This dynamo is made as a project at the course Mechatronics Engineering Design at Technical University of Denmark.

Besides the print you'll need:
a diode
a small motor
three screws of appropriate size to fasten the body and gear parts. Print the parts (the part name tells how many of each part should be printed). Assemble as shown in the assembly-picture. Attach a diode to the motor.
